Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made by Ford GoBike system. This data file corresponds to February 2019 in San Francisco Bay area. The various features included in the dataset are:

  • Trip Duration (seconds)
  • Start Time along with date
  • End Time along with date
  • Start Station ID
  • Start Station Name
  • Start Station Latitude
  • Start Station Longitude
  • End Station ID
  • End Station Name
  • End Station Latitude
  • End Station Longitude
  • Bike ID
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer)
  • Member birth year.
  • Member gender.
  • bike_share_for_all_trip.

Limitations¶

  • There are some missing data in multiple columns.

Problems¶

  • duration_sec is hard to understand and grasp.
  • start_time and end_time are strings holding a datetime.
  • start_station_id and end_station_id should be string instead of float.
  • bike_id should be string instead of integer.
  • age would be a more useful feature to explore rather then member_birth_year.

Cleaning¶

Define¶

create two new column duration_minutes and duration_hours to store the duration in minutes and hours Respectively.

Code¶

In [8]:
df['duration_minutes'] = df['duration_sec'] / 60
df['duration_hours'] = df['duration_sec'] / 3600

Define¶

convert start_time and end_time to datetime.

Code¶

In [10]:
def convert_to_datetime(df, columns):
    """
    This function converts the type of columns in a dataframe to datetime
    parameters:
    df: The dataframe.
    columns: a list of strings that are the columns to convert.
    """
    for col in columns:
        df[col] = pd.to_datetime(df[col])
In [11]:
convert_to_datetime(df, ['start_time', 'end_time'])

Define¶

convert start_station_id and end_station_id to a 3 digit string.

Code¶

In [13]:
def convert_to_string(df, columns, length):
    for col in columns:
        df[col] = df[col].astype('Int64').astype('str').str.zfill(length)
In [14]:
convert_to_string(df, ['start_station_id', 'end_station_id'], 3)

Which are the most active stations?¶

In [28]:
# Counting the number of stations that were the start of the ride
start = df['start_station_name'].value_counts()
# Counting the number of stations that were the end of the ride
end = df['end_station_name'].value_counts()
# Joining the two series in a dataframe
active_stations = start.to_frame().join(end)
# Summing the start and end counts
active_stations['activity'] = active_stations['start_station_name'] + active_stations['end_station_name']
# sorting the values from most active to lowest active
active_stations.sort_values('activity', ascending=False, inplace=True)

The next plot will show the top 10 most active stations only.

In [29]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5), dpi=200)
plt.barh(active_stations.index[9::-1], active_stations.activity[9::-1])
plt.title('Top 10 most active bike stations')
plt.xlabel('activity')
plt.show()

Insights

  • San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St) is the most active bike station with 3544 starting bike rides and 4857 ending bike rides.
  • The second and third most active stations are Market St at 10th St and Montgomery St BART Station (Market St at 2nd St) with 7877 and 6542 total rides respectively.

What are the main features of interest in the dataset?¶

The main features I focused on exploring in this notebook are:

  • duration_hours
  • start_station_latitude and start_station_longitude
  • end_station_latitude and end_station_longitude.

Varibales Distribution and Comminicating Results¶

  • For the duration, 95% of the trips take less than 30 minutes.

To represent the histograms of the duration in minutes and in hours, I had to convert the given seconds column to the respective unit. minutes = seconds/60 | hours = seconds/3600.

  • Most bike riders are subscribers, not customers and Males represent 75% of the users base.
  • The three most active bike stations are:
    1. San Francisco Caltrain Station 2
    2. Market St at 10th St
    3. Montgomery St BART Station

To find this I had to find the total number of appearances for the stations both as a starting point or an end destination. That number represents the amount of activity the station is receiving.

Unusual Distributions and Outliers¶

  • There is a negligible number of trip durations that are longer than 95% of the trip durations, That causes the duration distribution to be highly positively skewed.
  • There are some outliers in the age that can be noticed clearly in both the histogram of the distribution of the age and the boxplot. The outlier ages are over 100 years old.

Bivariate Exploration¶

What is the distribution of the stations on the map and their activity level?¶

In [39]:
# Get start and end stations and their activity
start_markers = df[['start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude']].value_counts().to_frame().reset_index().values
end_markers = df[['end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude']].value_counts().to_frame().reset_index().values
# Add a map
trip_map = folium.Map(location=[37.6087461354128, -122.14727351791509], zoom_start=9.5)
# Add the activity as a heatmap
HeatMap(data=start_markers).add_to(folium.FeatureGroup(name='Start Stations').add_to(trip_map))
HeatMap(data=end_markers).add_to(folium.FeatureGroup(name='End Stations').add_to(trip_map))
folium.LayerControl().add_to(trip_map)
trip_map

sns.boxplot(data=df[df['duration_minutes']<=35], x='duration_minutes', y='user_type', color=base_color)
plt.xlabel('Trip Duration in Minutes')
plt.ylabel('user Type')
plt.title("Boxplot of Trip Duration in Minutes for every User Type (Limited to 35 Minutes)")
plt.show()

Insights

  • In general, Subscribers trip durations are shorter than casual Customers trip durations.
  • This might me due to the fact that Subscribers are already paying so might as well use the bikes all the time even for short durations of time.

Multivariate Exploration¶

What is the Correlation between variables in the dataset?¶

In [47]:
# function encode features as numerical variables
def l_encoder(df, columns):
    for col in columns:
        label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
        df[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df.loc[:,col])
    return df
In [48]:
df_enc = df.copy()
df_enc = l_encoder(df_enc, ['member_gender', 'user_type', 'bike_share_for_all_trip', 'end_station_id', 'start_station_id', 'bike_id'])
In [49]:

plt.title("Correlation Matrix")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Insights

  • There is a strong positive correlation between the latitude of both start and end stations and longitude of both start and end stations.
  • The duration in all its units is 100% correlated as expected.
  • The negative 100% correlation between age and member_birth_year is logical.

What is the Correlation between specific numeric variables in the dataset?¶

In [51]:
df_enc.dropna(inplace=True)
g = sns.PairGrid(data=df_enc, vars=['duration_minutes', 'start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'member_birth_year', 'age'])
g.map_diag(plt.hist)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter, alpha=0.2)
g.fig.set_size_inches(11, 9)
g.fig.dpi = 200
g.fig.suptitle("PairGrid plot of different numerical features", fontsize=20, y=1.05)
plt.show()

Insights

  • There is no correlation between duration and any of the other 4 numeric variables.
  • member_birth_year and age are negatively correlated which is expected.
  • start_station_id and end_station_id are not correlated with any other variable.
  • The distribution of age is positively skewed which makes member_birth_year negatively skewed.

Conclusions¶

  • 95% of the trips take less than 30 minutes.
  • Most bike riders are Subscribers, not customers and Males represent 75% of the users base.

  • From the coordinates of the stations and their frequencies; There three main areas of activity on San Fransisco Bay area that are:

    1. San Fransisco
    2. Oakland
    3. San Jose

  • The three most active bike stations are:

    1. San Francisco Caltrain Station 2
    2. Market St at 10th St
    3. Montgomery St BART Station

  • In general, Male trip durations tend to be shorter than Female trip durations.

  • Subscribers trip durations are shorter than Customers trip durations.

  • The distributions of age with respect to user types are similar. Hence, there is no relationship between age and user_type.

  • Female have the youngest median age of 31 years old, followed by Male with 32 years old.

Limitations¶

  • There are a few missing data.
  • There are a few outliers when it comes to age.
